To send HTML-formatted emails in C#, you'll primarily use the `System.Net.Mail` namespace.

First, create a `MailMessage` object. This object holds all the email's details. Set the `IsBodyHtml` property of the `MailMessage` to `true`. This crucial step tells the mail client that the `Body` property contains HTML, not plain text.

```csharp
using System.Net.Mail;
using System.Net;

// ...

MailMessage mail = new MailMessage();
mail.From = new MailAddress("your_email@example.com");
mail.To.Add("recipient_email@example.com");
mail.Subject = "HTML Email Subject";
mail.IsBodyHtml = true; // THIS IS KEY!

string htmlBody = @"
    <h1>Welcome!</h1>
    <p>This is an <b>HTML-formatted</b> email from C#.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Item 1</li>
        <li>Item 2</li>
    </ul>
    <img src='cid:myImage' alt='Embedded Image' />"; // Example with embedded image

mail.Body = htmlBody;
```

For sending, you'll use a `SmtpClient`. Configure it with your SMTP server details (host, port, credentials, SSL).

```csharp
SmtpClient smtpClient = new SmtpClient("smtp.yourprovider.com");
smtpClient.Port = 587; // Or 465 for SSL
smtpClient.Credentials = new NetworkCredential("your_username", "your_password");
smtpClient.EnableSsl = true;

try
{
    smtpClient.Send(mail);
    Console.WriteLine("HTML email sent successfully!");
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Error sending email: {ex.Message}");
}
```

You can also embed images by adding `LinkedResource` objects to the `AlternateViews` of the `MailMessage`. This allows images to appear directly within the email body.

Sending HTML-formatted emails in C# is straightforward using the `System.Net.Mail` namespace.

First, create a `MailMessage` object. This object represents the email itself. You'll specify the sender, recipients, subject, and the body.

```csharp
using System.Net.Mail;
using System.Net;

// ... inside a method or class

MailMessage mail = new MailMessage();
mail.From = new MailAddress("your_email@example.com");
mail.To.Add("recipient@example.com");
mail.Subject = "HTML Email from C#";
```

The crucial part for HTML formatting is setting the `IsBodyHtml` property of the `MailMessage` object to `true`. Then, you can assign your HTML string to the `Body` property.

```csharp
mail.IsBodyHtml = true;
mail.Body = "<h1>Hello from C#!</h1><p>This is an <strong>HTML-formatted</strong> email.</p><p>You can include links: <a href='https://www.google.com'>Google</a></p>";
```

Next, you need an `SmtpClient` to send the email. You'll configure it with your SMTP server details, port, and credentials.

```csharp
SmtpClient smtp = new SmtpClient("smtp.yourprovider.com"); // e.g., smtp.gmail.com
smtp.Port = 587; // or 465 for SSL
smtp.EnableSsl = true; // Use SSL/TLS
smtp.Credentials = new NetworkCredential("your_email@example.com", "your_email_password"); // Your email and app password (if applicable)

try
{
    smtp.Send(mail);
    Console.WriteLine("HTML Email sent successfully!");
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Error sending email: " + ex.Message);
}
```

Remember to replace placeholders like `your_email@example.com`, `recipient@example.com`, `smtp.yourprovider.com`, and `your_email_password` with your actual email credentials and server information. For services like Gmail, you might need to generate an "App Password" if you have two-factor authentication enabled.

Sending HTML-formatted emails in C# is straightforward using the `System.Net.Mail` namespace.

First, you'll need to create an instance of the `MailMessage` class. This object represents the email itself. Set the `From`, `To`, `Subject`, and `Body` properties. The crucial part for HTML is setting the `IsBodyHtml` property to `true`. This tells the email client to interpret the `Body` content as HTML rather than plain text. You can then embed your HTML markup directly into the `Body` string.

Here's a basic example:

```csharp
using System.Net.Mail;
using System.Net;

public class EmailSender
{
    public void SendHtmlEmail(string recipientEmail, string subject, string htmlBody)
    {
        try
        {
            MailMessage mail = new MailMessage();
            mail.From = new MailAddress("your_email@example.com"); // Your sender email
            mail.To.Add(recipientEmail);
            mail.Subject = subject;
            mail.IsBodyHtml = true; // Crucial for HTML formatting
            mail.Body = htmlBody; // Your HTML content

            SmtpClient smtpClient = new SmtpClient("smtp.example.com"); // Your SMTP server
            smtpClient.Port = 587; // Common port for TLS/SSL
            smtpClient.Credentials = new NetworkCredential("your_email@example.com", "your_email_password"); // Your email credentials
            smtpClient.EnableSsl = true; // Enable SSL for secure connection

            smtpClient.Send(mail);
            Console.WriteLine("HTML email sent successfully!");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"Error sending HTML email: {ex.Message}");
        }
    }
}

// Example usage:
// var sender = new EmailSender();
// string htmlContent = "<h1>Welcome!</h1><p>This is an <strong>HTML-formatted</strong> email.</p><img src='https://via.placeholder.com/150' alt='Placeholder Image'>";
// sender.SendHtmlEmail("recipient@example.com", "HTML Test Email", htmlContent);
```

Remember to replace placeholders like `"your_email@example.com"`, `"smtp.example.com"`, and `"your_email_password"` with your actual email provider's details. For production environments, it's highly recommended to store sensitive information like passwords securely, perhaps in environment variables or a configuration file, rather than hardcoding them.
